  "prompt": "Is morning sickness a sign of good pregnancy?",
  "response": "While morning sickness can be a sign of a healthy pregnancy, it is not a definitive indicator that everything is okay. Here are some key points about morning sickness:\n\n1. Morning sickness is common\n- Affects about 50-80% of pregnant women\n- Usually occurs during the first trimester\n- Can involve nausea, vomiting, or both\n\n2. Potential positive signs\n- May indicate normal hormonal changes\n- Can be a sign of a healthy placenta\n- Some studies suggest it might indicate lower miscarriage risk\n\n3. However, not experiencing morning sickness is also normal\n- About 20-30% of women don't experience morning sickness\n- Absence doesn't mean there's a problem with the pregnancy\n\n4. When to be concerned\n- Severe, persistent vomiting (hyperemesis gravidarum)\n- Unable to keep food or fluids down\n- Signs of dehydration\n\n5. Best approach\n- Regular prenatal check-ups\n- Discuss symptoms with healthcare provider\n- Each pregnancy is unique\n\nRemember that while morning sickness can be a positive sign, it's not a guaranteed indicator of a healthy pregnancy. Always consult with a healthcare professional for personalized medical advice.",
